d. It shows how Benedictine convents were both cut-off and enclosed yet very much in touch with the religious and political developments at home, but also proposes a different approach to the history of nuns, with a study of emotions and the senses in the cloister, delving into the textual analysis of the nuns' personal and communal documents to explore aspect of a lived spirituality, when the body which so often hindered the spirit, at times enabled spiritual experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBenedictine nunsxHistoryy17th century. 0aCatholics, EnglishzEuropexHistoryy17th century. 0aMonasticism and religious orders for womenzEuropexHistoryy17th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aConvents.  aEarly modern.  aEmotions.  aNuns.  aSenses.1 aLux-Sterritt, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611004640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526110046423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526110046/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles